{"questionId":"19897","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Dana has collected some data regarding the heights <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> (metres) of waves against a pier at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn></math> randomly chosen times in a single day. This data is shown in the table below.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/9ec7e13106ac7d248e4a3acfa98cd2a86e4e4002.png\"></p>\n<p>She wishes to perform a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>-test at the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>%</mo></math> significance level to see if the height of waves&nbsp;could be modelled by a normal distribution. Her null hypothesis is</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>H</mtext><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></math> The data can be modelled by a normal distribution.</p>\n<p>From the table she calculates the mean of the heights in her sample to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>828</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math> and the&nbsp;standard deviation of the heights <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math> to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>257</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>She calculates the expected values for each interval under this null hypothesis, and some&nbsp;of these values are shown in the table below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/2652358763dd5e151599b1cdf934c24e42c7d2a8.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> test statistic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msubsup><mi>χ</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfenced></math>&nbsp;for this test.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><img src=\"__IMG__/7cb502eeaaff1d2bb5dae3f914699dc077a20bd6.png\"></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>χ</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>35</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>(M1)A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19897","referenceCode":"EXN.2.AHL.TZ0.3c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the value of the χ2 test statistic χcalc2 for this test.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.10—Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}